		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64448488"><p><div class="quote"><p>But there was one glimmer of insight into the 20-horse race. When asked to choose the top four finishers in order, HorseGPT repeated those same losing picks &mdash; which finished #2, #15, and #20. But then it added two more underdogs for fourth place finishers, "based on their potential to outperform expectations under muddy conditions." One of those two horses &mdash; Domestic Product &mdash; finished in 13th place. But the other of the two horses was Mystik Dan &mdash; who came in first.</p></div><p>This wasn't a glimmer of insight.  It's completely irrelevant that one of the two choices it picked to come in 4th on a muddy track happened to win on a fast (dry) track.  There was no possible betting strategy which would have earned a profit on these picks. And it would not have made these picks with the correct track condition.</p><p>Even if it had picked these 5 horses as potential winners on an accurate conditions, it still had a 25% chance of being right - making this a prediction about as reliable as "predicting" on a 4 answer multiple choice question.</p><p>HorseGPT was always going to be bad at its stated purpose, if had <i>any</i> value, they would have kept it private and made way more money betting the races than they could ever make selling the AI.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64448488">
